            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 74-year-old retired schoolteacher who lives alone in a modest suburban home, following the passing of her husband three years ago. She has two adult daughters who live nearby and are closely involved in her care. A warm and resilient woman, {patientName} has always been active in her community — she enjoys tending to her garden, attending weekly watercolor painting classes, and volunteering at the local library twice a week. She is a non-smoker and drinks only an occasional glass of wine on social occasions.\n\nOver the past six months, {patientName} has noticed a gradual but worrying change in her bowel habits — alternating between constipation and loose stools — accompanied by crampy lower abdominal discomfort that she initially attributed to \"getting older.\" More recently, she has experienced episodes of rectal bleeding (dark red streaks in stool), significant fatigue, and an unintentional weight loss of approximately 7 kg over four months. These symptoms finally prompted her daughters to insist she see her primary care physician.\n\nOn presentation, {patientName} appears pale and mildly cachectic, with a slightly distended abdomen and vague tenderness in the right lower quadrant. She is soft-spoken but anxious about her diagnosis, asking thoughtful questions at each appointment. She has mild bilateral ankle edema and moves slowly due to mild arthritic discomfort in her knees.\n\n{patientName} was referred promptly for colonoscopy, which revealed a large, partially obstructing, ulcerated mass in the ascending colon. Biopsy confirmed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma. Subsequent staging CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis showed no distant metastases (Stage II–III). She is currently being evaluated by a multidisciplinary oncology team for surgical and adjuvant chemotherapy planning.\n\nDespite her diagnosis, {patientName} remains determined and positive. She continues her painting classes when energy allows and talks daily with her daughters by phone. Her primary concerns are maintaining her independence and quality of life throughout treatment."
